      </p>
      <p><code>--font-mono</code></p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="letter-spacing-tracking">Letter spacing (tracking)</h2>

  <p>Tracking adjusts the space between all letters in a block of text. The rules are simple:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Large text:</strong> Tighten slightly (<code>--tracking-tight</code>) — Large letters
      have more natural whitespace
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Body text:</strong> Never touch (<code>--tracking-normal: 0</code>) — The font
      designer optimized it
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Small text:</strong> Loosen slightly (<code>--tracking-wide</code>) — Improves
      legibility
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>All caps:</strong> Always loosen (<code>--tracking-wide</code>) — Capital letters need
      breathing room
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="influences">Influences</h2>

  <p>This typographic system draws from several traditions:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Robert Bringhurst</strong> — <em>The Elements of Typographic Style</em>, the bible of
      typography
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Edward Tufte</strong> — Information design principles, especially regarding whitespace
      and data density
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Swiss/International Style</strong> — Grid systems, systematic thinking, restraint
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Massimo Vignelli</strong> — "Systematic, not rigid" — rules that enable rather than constrain
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="for-content-authors">For content authors</h2>

